50:40.080 --> 50:42.685
[SPEAKER_06]: Could you answer Rishi Sunak's point, please, Keir Starmer?

50:42.705 --> 50:44.387
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, I will when I can get a word in edgeways.

50:45.349 --> 50:48.514
[SPEAKER_06]: His record is of saying, I'm not going to get in the room to negotiate.

50:48.935 --> 50:49.836
[SPEAKER_06]: And what have we got?

50:49.816 --> 50:51.639
[SPEAKER_06]: We've been in the room to negotiate.

50:51.659 --> 50:52.320
[SPEAKER_06]: What have we got?

50:52.340 --> 50:52.941
[SPEAKER_06]: Ongoing strikes.

50:52.961 --> 50:53.361
[SPEAKER_06]: That's an answer.

50:53.562 --> 50:54.864
[SPEAKER_06]: We have to end these strikes.

50:55.144 --> 50:55.685
[SPEAKER_06]: How?

50:55.905 --> 51:01.774
[SPEAKER_06]: The grown-up way to do that is to get in the room and to negotiate with the doctors and come to a settlement.

51:01.794 --> 51:03.136
[SPEAKER_06]: There's only two ways forward.

51:03.477 --> 51:07.583
[SPEAKER_06]: One is a continuing strike, which is what we've had for a very, very long time.

51:07.783 --> 51:09.866
[SPEAKER_06]: We're now four and a half weeks from election.

51:09.886 --> 51:11.529
[SPEAKER_06]: He's going to kick it into the long grass.

51:12.110 --> 51:14.994
[SPEAKER_06]: Or you get grown up, you go in the room and you resolve this.

51:15.034 --> 51:16.296
[SPEAKER_06]: That does not mean

51:16.276 --> 51:18.839
[SPEAKER_06]: If you agree with the 35%, we can't afford that.

51:18.859 --> 51:19.200
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

51:19.220 --> 51:22.824
[SPEAKER_06]: But we have got to settle on this point.

51:22.904 --> 51:31.474
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm going to pause that there, please, because I want to return to another part of Janet's question that you did touch on, that she lost her cousin, who was waiting for surgery.

51:31.514 --> 51:34.918
[SPEAKER_16]: These waiting lists are a matter of life and death.

51:35.079 --> 51:37.502
[SPEAKER_16]: A quick point of information to both of you.

51:37.962 --> 51:42.047
[SPEAKER_16]: If you had loved ones on a long waiting list for surgery,

51:42.027 --> 51:47.556
[SPEAKER_16]: Would you, if you felt that that was the only way forward, use private healthcare, Rishi Sunak?

51:47.896 --> 51:48.117
[SPEAKER_14]: Yes.

51:48.838 --> 51:49.539
[SPEAKER_16]: Keir Starmer?

51:49.739 --> 51:49.940
[SPEAKER_16]: No.

51:50.981 --> 51:55.228
[SPEAKER_16]: Absolutely no, if your loved one was on a waiting list for surgery?

51:56.010 --> 51:56.210
[SPEAKER_16]: No.

51:56.631 --> 51:57.472
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you very much.

51:58.353 --> 51:59.956
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't use private health.

52:00.757 --> 52:02.039
[SPEAKER_06]: I use the NHS.

52:02.180 --> 52:05.605
[SPEAKER_06]: That's where my wife works, in one of the big hospitals.

52:06.952 --> 52:08.535
[SPEAKER_06]: It runs through my dear...

52:08.836 --> 52:09.637
[SPEAKER_16]: Okay, thank you.

52:09.677 --> 52:12.022
[SPEAKER_16]: We've had the answers to that very clearly.

52:12.042 --> 52:16.470
[SPEAKER_16]: I just want to pause there to move on to a different aspect of the debate on the NHS.

52:17.031 --> 52:22.161
[SPEAKER_16]: Everyone knows that fixing the NHS depends on fixing social care.

52:22.862 --> 52:27.711
